Dialogue: 0,0:00:00.11,0:00:02.18,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}- Hi, it's me, Tim Dodd, the Everyday Astronaut.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:02.18,0:00:07.21,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}It's been 50 years since Neil Armstrong famously stepped off the footpad of an Apollo Lunar Lander
Dialogue: 0,0:00:07.21,0:00:11.87,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}and onto a new celestial body for the first time in human history.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:11.87,0:00:14.08,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}And once he was safely standing on the surface of the moon
Dialogue: 0,0:00:14.08,0:00:17.67,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}he spoke perhaps some of the most famous words of all time.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:17.67,0:00:25.76,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}- [Neil Armstrong] It's one small step for man, one giant leap for mankind.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:25.76,0:00:28.29,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}- But something about this always confused me.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:28.29,0:00:34.55,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}I mean, sure, the step off of the lunar lander's 91 centimeter footpad was a nice easy and small step,
Dialogue: 0,0:00:34.55,0:00:38.38,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}but the step just before that was actually enormous.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:38.38,0:00:39.86,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}I'm talking about this.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:39.86,0:00:43.50,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}The huge gap between the last rung of the ladder and the ground.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:43.50,0:00:47.29,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}I mean why on the moon is that gap so huge?
Dialogue: 0,0:00:47.29,0:00:50.82,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}Isn't it dangerous to require an astronaut to jump down onto the surface
Dialogue: 0,0:00:50.82,0:00:52.51,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}and then have to jump back up?
Dialogue: 0,0:00:52.51,0:00:54.47,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}The lunar lander's ladder had nine rungs,
Dialogue: 0,0:00:54.47,0:00:58.18,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}all spaced out at 22.8 centimeters apart from each other.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:58.18,0:01:01.00,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}But the gap between the last rung and the ground
Dialogue: 0,0:01:01.00,0:01:05.36,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}was about three times that, at a whopping 76 centimeters.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:05.36,0:01:09.07,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}So really the ladder wasn't missing one rung,
Dialogue: 0,0:01:09.07,0:01:10.41,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}it was missing two.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:10.41,0:01:12.97,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}I mean, sure, the gravity's only one sixth that of Earth's,
Dialogue: 0,0:01:12.97,0:01:17.38,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}but wouldn't it have been so much safer if there was even just one more rung
Dialogue: 0,0:01:17.38,0:01:19.60,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}that closed that gap up just a little.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:19.60,0:01:20.97,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}So today we're gonna look into
Dialogue: 0,0:01:20.97,0:01:25.15,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}why NASA and the lunar lander's manufacturer Grumman chose a ladder of this length.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:25.15,0:01:28.43,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}We'll then talk about all the design considerations of the hardware,
Dialogue: 0,0:01:28.43,0:01:31.45,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}the unknown conditions of the lunar surface itself,
Dialogue: 0,0:01:31.45,0:01:35.57,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}and the astronauts who were basically just too smooth of pilots
Dialogue: 0,0:01:35.57,0:01:39.42,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}to get the ladder's last rung any closer to the surface of the moon.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:39.42,0:01:40.35,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}Lets get started.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:51.83,0:01:53.79,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}- On May 25th, 1961,
Dialogue: 0,0:01:53.79,0:01:56.06,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}President John F. Kennedy announced his goal
Dialogue: 0,0:01:56.06,0:01:59.52,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}of putting humans on the moon by the end of the decade to Congress.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:59.52,0:02:02.34,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}At the time of this historic and ambitious announcement,
Dialogue: 0,0:02:02.34,0:02:08.07,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}the U.S. had exactly 15 minutes and 22 seconds of human space flight experience
Dialogue: 0,0:02:08.07,0:02:11.36,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}with just one suborbital launch under their belt.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:11.36,0:02:14.40,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}By the way, I should probably mention that Kennedy's speech in front of Congress
Dialogue: 0,0:02:14.40,0:02:17.44,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}is not the famous {\i1}We choose to go to the moon{\i0} speech.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:17.44,0:02:20.77,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}That happened over a year later at Rice Stadium in Houston.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:20.77,0:02:25.44,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}But the point is this insanely ambitious goal almost immediately put a lot of things in motion.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:25.44,0:02:27.81,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}A tsunami of engineering ensued.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:27.81,0:02:28.94,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}I mean so much so,
Dialogue: 0,0:02:28.94,0:02:32.33,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}sometimes it feels like the left hand didn't know what the right hand was doing.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:32.33,0:02:36.70,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}One item that almost immediately began development was the lunar lander itself.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:36.70,0:02:41.75,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}In July 1962, 11 companies were asked to submit proposals for a lunar lander.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:41.75,0:02:46.42,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}Grumman won the contract and began to design mock-ups as early as 1963.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:46.42,0:02:49.65,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}Wait, what's all this have to do with a ladder?
Dialogue: 0,0:02:49.65,0:02:51.51,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}Well, hold up, I'm setting up a story here
Dialogue: 0,0:02:51.51,0:02:55.16,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}and to me, these stories are half the fun, these little fun nuggets of history.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:55.16,0:03:00.57,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}But this particular bit of history is one of the key reasons why the ladder is the wrong length.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:00.57,0:03:06.46,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}Grumman was building a lander intended to land on a surface that we knew literally nothing about.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:06.46,0:03:09.17,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}This is understandable when the only data we had at the time
Dialogue: 0,0:03:09.17,0:03:11.98,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}was from the orbiters taking footage from the ranger missions.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:11.98,0:03:15.87,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}And before that, we just had ground based telescopes here on Earth.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:15.87,0:03:21.46,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}Well, I guess actually Ranger 6 through 9 actually recorded footage all the way up until impact,
Dialogue: 0,0:03:21.46,0:03:26.05,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}resulting in some footage with an impressive resolution of .3 meters.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:26.05,0:03:31.10,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}But, we still had almost no idea of what the surface of the moon was actually like.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:31.10,0:03:33.42,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}It wouldn't be until June 2nd, 1966,
Dialogue: 0,0:03:33.42,0:03:36.31,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}before the U.S. would soft land surveyor one on the moon,
Dialogue: 0,0:03:36.31,0:03:39.32,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}some four months after the Soviet Union landed Luna 9.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:39.32,0:03:45.04,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}This would be the first time there'd be any data available to the U.S. about the composition of the moon's surface.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:45.04,0:03:47.78,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}And even so, it was quite limited.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:47.78,0:03:50.54,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}This means during the first three years of development of the lunar lander,
Dialogue: 0,0:03:50.54,0:03:53.12,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}there were countless question marks.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:53.12,0:03:56.37,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}Many scientists thought the surface might be so soft and powdery,
Dialogue: 0,0:03:56.37,0:04:01.35,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}it might swallow a spacecraft or people entirely on the surface,
Dialogue: 0,0:04:01.35,0:04:03.82,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}sinking them so deep they wouldn't be able to get out.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:03.82,0:04:07.36,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}While NASA was busy sending spacecraft after spacecraft to observe the moon,
Dialogue: 0,0:04:07.36,0:04:10.14,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}Grumman was deep in development of the lunar lander.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:10.14,0:04:12.46,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}The first couple years saw a lot of changes,
Dialogue: 0,0:04:12.46,0:04:16.00,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}including things like going from five legs to four legs,
Dialogue: 0,0:04:16.00,0:04:19.49,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}from a round cockpit to more of a polyhedral shape,
Dialogue: 0,0:04:19.49,0:04:22.63,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}and even going from a round hatch to a square hatch.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:22.63,0:04:27.62,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}Oh by the way, that round hatch led to astronauts really struggling to get back into the spacecraft,
Dialogue: 0,0:04:27.62,0:04:32.94,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}so Grumman switched to a square version to help make egress and ingress that much easier.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:32.94,0:04:38.01,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}This is also around the same time that Grumman was playing around with using a rope instead of a ladder,
Dialogue: 0,0:04:38.01,0:04:41.32,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}which astronauts found to actually be impossible,
Dialogue: 0,0:04:41.32,0:04:45.90,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}and despite them using a peter pan pulley system which would simulate one sixth gravity.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:45.90,0:04:49.62,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}So Grumman opted for a ladder down the front leg of the lunar lander.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:49.62,0:04:52.09,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}But even with something as simple as a ladder,
Dialogue: 0,0:04:52.09,0:04:54.16,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}weight was an enormous factor.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:54.16,0:04:57.58,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}I mean, after all, for each kilogram landed on the surface of the moon,
Dialogue: 0,0:04:57.58,0:05:01.40,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}it takes about 400 kilograms of rocket to launch from Earth.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:01.40,0:05:03.91,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}This means Grumman went to great lengths to cut weight
Dialogue: 0,0:05:03.95,0:05:08.80,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}including ditching seats and using lightweight golden kapton foil for insulation,
Dialogue: 0,0:05:08.80,0:05:12.10,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}but it also means the ladder, like all things,
Dialogue: 0,0:05:12.10,0:05:14.41,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}needed to be extremely lightweight.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:14.41,0:05:16.33,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}For example, I think my favorite thing to think about is
Dialogue: 0,0:05:16.40,0:05:19.44,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}how if the lunar lander were standing on its own legs here on Earth,
Dialogue: 0,0:05:19.44,0:05:21.53,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}it would've likely collapsed under its own weight
Dialogue: 0,0:05:21.53,0:05:24.53,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}because those legs weren't meant for Earth's gravity.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:24.53,0:05:27.36,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}They were only designed to handle the moon's weaker gravity.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:27.36,0:05:29.04,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}And the same thing goes for the ladder.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:29.04,0:05:32.43,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}If we were to try to ascend the ladder, the actual ladder, here on Earth,
Dialogue: 0,0:05:32.43,0:05:36.05,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}it would've likely broken because it's not meant to handle Earth's gravity.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:36.05,0:05:37.75,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}So they made it as lightweight as possible,
Dialogue: 0,0:05:37.75,0:05:40.91,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}and only capable of handling one sixth gravity.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:40.91,0:05:45.04,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}But weight likely isn't the main reason why the ladder stopped short of the surface.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:45.04,0:05:48.34,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}For this, we need to look at the landing gear the ladder is affixed to.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:48.34,0:05:50.76,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}The landing gear were designed to absorb the energy of impact
Dialogue: 0,0:05:50.76,0:05:52.94,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}and keep the LEM(Lunar Excursion Module) from toppling over.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:52.94,0:05:56.64,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}Grumman engineers were incredibly concerned with the LEM tipping over,
Dialogue: 0,0:05:56.64,0:06:00.08,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}so a significant amount of work went into the design of the landing gear.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:00.08,0:06:04.75,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}The landing gear was so vital that after the command module on the lunar excursion module undocked,
Dialogue: 0,0:06:04.75,0:06:09.23,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}the command module pilot was instructed to visually inspect all four legs
Dialogue: 0,0:06:09.23,0:06:12.30,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}to make sure they were properly deployed from their stowed position.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:12.30,0:06:16.06,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}A leg that wasn't properly locked in place would've been an immediate abort.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:16.06,0:06:18.62,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}But fortunately, none of them failed to deploy.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:18.62,0:06:23.16,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}One interesting design consideration was the invention of a single use shock absorber.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:23.16,0:06:26.90,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}NASA and Grumman developed a crushable honeycomb aluminum cartridge,
Dialogue: 0,0:06:26.90,0:06:28.50,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}otherwise known as a crush core.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:28.50,0:06:31.37,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}There was a great concern about using hydraulics in the landing gear
Dialogue: 0,0:06:31.37,0:06:34.55,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}and fear that they could leak and leave a landing leg unusable.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:34.55,0:06:39.83,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}So, for simplicity's sake, they went with the crush core which is basically just a set of cartridges
Dialogue: 0,0:06:39.83,0:06:44.88,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}made of aluminum that either compress or stretch to provide smooth and reliable resistance.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:44.88,0:06:48.02,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}This technology is still used today for certain applications.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:48.02,0:06:53.03,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}Actually, SpaceX has crush core in the landing struts of their Falcon 9 rockets.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:53.03,0:06:55.36,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}If the hydraulic shock absorbers bottom out,
Dialogue: 0,0:06:55.36,0:06:58.43,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}they have additional travel in the single use crush core.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:58.43,0:07:00.60,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}This was very obvious on Thaicom 8,
Dialogue: 0,0:07:00.60,0:07:04.23,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}which launched and landed on May 27th, 2016.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:04.23,0:07:06.96,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}The booster had a little bit of a rough landing,
Dialogue: 0,0:07:06.96,0:07:10.40,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}resulting in one of the landing legs eating into the crush core
Dialogue: 0,0:07:10.40,0:07:12.82,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}which made the booster stand lopsided.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:12.82,0:07:16.14,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}By some miracle, the booster made it all the way back home,
Dialogue: 0,0:07:16.14,0:07:19.46,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}despite some really, really close calls.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:26.41,0:07:27.75,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}But back to the lunar lander.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:27.75,0:07:31.09,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}Its legs could absorb a large amount of impact velocity.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:31.09,0:07:33.03,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}And due to their crush core absorbers,
Dialogue: 0,0:07:33.03,0:07:36.13,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}they did not rebound like a traditional hydraulic absorber.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:36.13,0:07:39.09,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}They just compressed and then they stayed in that position.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:39.09,0:07:44.37,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}They were designed to handle up to three meters per second of vertical velocity with zero horizontal velocity,
Dialogue: 0,0:07:44.37,0:07:50.62,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}or up to 2.1 meters per second with 1.2 meters per second of horizontal velocity,
Dialogue: 0,0:07:50.62,0:07:52.63,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}which they could handle very reliably.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:52.63,0:07:57.02,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}Now since NASA didn't know how much the shock absorbers would stroke or compress,
Dialogue: 0,0:07:57.02,0:08:01.13,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}and they were unsure of how deep into the lunar surface the LEM might sink,
Dialogue: 0,0:08:01.13,0:08:04.71,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}they didn't want the ladder attached to the movable part of the strut
Dialogue: 0,0:08:04.71,0:08:06.75,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}and potentially hinder any movement.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:06.75,0:08:11.39,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}As a matter of fact, NASA assumed the struts would travel a lot more than they did.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:11.39,0:08:15.47,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}Come to find out, two factors prevented them from actually traveling that much,
Dialogue: 0,0:08:15.47,0:08:20.51,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}the pilots' skills and the surface of the moon's ability to absorb energy.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:20.51,0:08:21.40,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}That's right.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:21.40,0:08:27.26,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}The pilots were in a sense maybe too gentle with the LEM and they all landed so stinking softly,
Dialogue: 0,0:08:27.26,0:08:30.49,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}there was hardly any perceivable travel on the legs.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:30.49,0:08:33.38,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}But then again, there were so many unknown variables.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:33.38,0:08:36.49,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}NASA was playing this whole thing extremely safe.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:36.49,0:08:38.49,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}The astronauts were instructed to cut the engine
Dialogue: 0,0:08:38.51,0:08:44.64,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}when one of three 1.5 meter long lunar surface sensing probes made contact with the surface.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:44.64,0:08:47.34,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}You've probably heard them make that contact call out.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:01.84,0:09:03.20,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}This was intended to not only help
Dialogue: 0,0:09:03.22,0:09:08.97,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}prevent the engine from kicking up too much debris and dust for visibility and hole puncture concerns,
Dialogue: 0,0:09:08.97,0:09:12.43,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}but it's also because the engine had engine thrust decay.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:12.43,0:09:15.31,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}This is where even after successful shutdown of the engine,
Dialogue: 0,0:09:15.31,0:09:20.42,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}there's still some residual pressure that can last anywhere from half a second to a few seconds.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:20.42,0:09:21.96,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}All rocket engines have this.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:21.96,0:09:22.79,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}Fun side note,
Dialogue: 0,0:09:22.79,0:09:26.03,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}this little bit of extra thrust decay went unnoticed on the test stand
Dialogue: 0,0:09:26.03,0:09:30.95,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}when SpaceX upgraded their Merlin engine between flights two and three of their Falcon 1 rocket.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:30.95,0:09:32.01,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}After safe separation,
Dialogue: 0,0:09:32.01,0:09:35.92,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}additional thrust decay led to a collision of the first and second stage,
Dialogue: 0,0:09:35.92,0:09:37.55,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}causing a loss of the vehicle.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:37.55,0:09:41.73,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}The Apollo commander were intended to cut the engine at 1.5 meters in altitude,
Dialogue: 0,0:09:41.73,0:09:45.14,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}which would've been the right height to touchdown at a safe velocity,
Dialogue: 0,0:09:45.14,0:09:49.35,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}and compress the legs enough based on what NASA thought would be an adequate amount.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:49.35,0:09:50.65,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}But despite all this,
Dialogue: 0,0:09:50.65,0:09:54.32,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}all six landings had very different actual impact velocities.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:54.32,0:09:56.79,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}Neil Armstrong gave Apollo 11 the softest touchdown
Dialogue: 0,0:09:56.79,0:10:00.15,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}with a vertical velocity of .54 meters per second.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:00.15,0:10:04.69,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}Apollo 17 was the next softest at .91 meters per second.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:04.69,0:10:08.51,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}Apollo 14 was next, at .94 meters per second.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:08.51,0:10:11.42,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}Then Apollo 12, at 1 meter per second.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:11.42,0:10:14.30,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}Apollo 16 at 1.7 meters per second.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:14.30,0:10:22.47,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}And lastly, Apollo 15's commander David Scott finally gave her the beans at 2.07 meters per second.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:22.47,0:10:25.51,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}But that still well within the operational range to the legs.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:25.51,0:10:30.01,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}And now a big concern was having the descent engine coming in contact with a lunar surface.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:30.01,0:10:34.62,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}And despite Apollo 15 carrying the additional mass of the lunar rover vehicle,
Dialogue: 0,0:10:34.62,0:10:38.26,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}having a 25 centimeter nozzle extension on the descent engine,
Dialogue: 0,0:10:38.26,0:10:41.48,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}landing on the steepest lunar slope of 11 degrees.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:41.48,0:10:44.72,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}And despite the nozzle actually buckling,
Dialogue: 0,0:10:44.72,0:10:48.76,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}the nozzle still didn't actually come in contact with the surface at all.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:48.76,0:10:51.30,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}The buckling of the nozzle was due to a buildup of pressure
Dialogue: 0,0:10:51.30,0:10:53.89,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}from firing the nozzle so close to the surface,
Dialogue: 0,0:10:53.89,0:10:56.87,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}and not from coming in contact with the surface itself.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:56.87,0:11:00.92,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}But another factor that was later accounted for on why the stress didn't compress that much,
Dialogue: 0,0:11:00.92,0:11:04.09,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}was the fact that due to the moon's somewhat powdery surface
Dialogue: 0,0:11:04.09,0:11:09.69,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}the surface itself would actually absorb around 80% of the impact velocity.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:09.69,0:11:13.89,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}And this is perhaps why the landing legs compressed so much less than they had planned,
Dialogue: 0,0:11:13.89,0:11:16.22,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}leaving the final rung higher than nominal.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:16.22,0:11:18.53,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}Okay, so basically the moral of the story is
Dialogue: 0,0:11:18.53,0:11:22.32,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}landing on the moon was a big fat question mark with the Apollo program.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:22.32,0:11:26.37,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}NASA took the most conservative approach to as many things as possible,
Dialogue: 0,0:11:26.37,0:11:28.46,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}including fail proof shock absorbers,
Dialogue: 0,0:11:28.46,0:11:30.77,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}additional thermal protection on the landing legs,
Dialogue: 0,0:11:30.77,0:11:32.03,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}big fat landing pads,
Dialogue: 0,0:11:32.03,0:11:34.11,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}and contact probes to name a few.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:34.11,0:11:37.52,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}Suffice to say they didn't wanna make the ladder any longer than necessary
Dialogue: 0,0:11:37.52,0:11:40.24,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}and potentially hinder movement of the landing gear.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:40.24,0:11:44.05,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}So assuming things went as planned and the shock absorbers went deep enough,
Dialogue: 0,0:11:44.05,0:11:47.06,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}the ladder would've been a nice and easy step.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:47.06,0:11:51.23,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}But all this said, the final step still worried some astronauts.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:51.23,0:11:56.19,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}The commanders were actually trained to immediately attempt to jump back up to the bottom rung,
Dialogue: 0,0:11:56.19,0:11:58.52,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}after initial descent down the ladder.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:58.52,0:12:04.08,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}This way the pilot who is still inside the LEM could assist if there is any struggle to make that large gap.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:04.08,0:12:07.96,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}Neil actually commented on this before he stepped off the lander's pad.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:25.68,0:12:28.25,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}Different astronauts had different experiences with the ladder.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:28.25,0:12:31.29,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}Such as Jim Irwin saying the ladder was a real struggle.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:31.29,0:12:34.18,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}And 170 centimeter tall Pete Conrad saying.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:39.50,0:12:43.05,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}So to summarize, the final rung height was a topic for much debate.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:43.05,0:12:44.69,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}But with all the unknown variables,
Dialogue: 0,0:12:44.69,0:12:48.52,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}a bounty out there for every single kilogram to be shaved from the vehicle,
Dialogue: 0,0:12:48.52,0:12:54.33,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}and figuring jumping up and down in one sixth gravity would make ascent and descent much easier.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:54.33,0:12:58.15,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}They also didn't know how much the lunar surface would absorb energy,
Dialogue: 0,0:12:58.15,0:13:03.00,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}so NASA left the bottom rung at it's final gap of 76 centimeters,
Dialogue: 0,0:13:03.00,0:13:06.06,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}from the bottom of the ladder to the top of the landing pad.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:06.06,0:13:07.48,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}Or maybe NASA could've just done
Dialogue: 0,0:13:07.48,0:13:12.91,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}what the Soviet Union planned to do with their LK Lunar Lander, and just used a hinge ladder.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:12.91,0:13:13.89,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}So what do you think?
Dialogue: 0,0:13:13.89,0:13:15.16,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}Did I help answer all your questions about
Dialogue: 0,0:13:15.20,0:13:18.87,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}why the lunar lander's ladder was the height that it was?
Dialogue: 0,0:13:18.87,0:13:22.35,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}Let me know if you have any other questions about this topic or about the Apollo program
Dialogue: 0,0:13:22.35,0:13:24.42,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}or just rocket science in general.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:24.42,0:13:27.81,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}And stay tuned, cause I have a lot of really awesome videos coming up.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:27.81,0:13:32.15,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}I owe a huge thank you to my patreon supporters for helping make content like this possible.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:32.15,0:13:34.76,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}So if you wanna help, maybe add your voice to these scripts
Dialogue: 0,0:13:34.76,0:13:37.36,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}or help catch airs before these videos come out,
Dialogue: 0,0:13:37.36,0:13:39.24,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}or even just talk with other space fans,
Dialogue: 0,0:13:39.24,0:13:44.86,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}consider becoming a patreon supporter by going to patreon.com/everydayastronaut
Dialogue: 0,0:13:44.86,0:13:47.53,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}where you'll gain exclusive access to our Reddit,
Dialogue: 0,0:13:47.53,0:13:51.46,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}our Discord channel, and some exclusive livestreams as well.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:51.46,0:13:52.30,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}Thank you.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:52.30,0:13:54.08,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}And while you're online, be sure and check out my webstore
Dialogue: 0,0:13:54.08,0:13:55.91,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}where you can find things like this shirt,
Dialogue: 0,0:13:55.91,0:13:58.05,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}which by the way is almost sold out.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:58.05,0:14:01.48,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}And that's because we do runs of shirts now so the quality's a lot higher.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:01.48,0:14:04.22,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}There's also custom tags and custom packaging.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:04.22,0:14:07.88,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}But there's also tons of things in this store that are kinda constantly,
Dialogue: 0,0:14:07.88,0:14:12.50,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}we're trying to keep up with all these things like Grid Fin Not-A-Coasters and mugs and hats,
Dialogue: 0,0:14:12.50,0:14:13.85,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}and lots of other fun stuff.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:13.85,0:14:15.47,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}So, be sure and check that out.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:15.47,0:14:16.61,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}And while you're on there,
Dialogue: 0,0:14:16.61,0:14:22.56,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}click on the music tab where you can listen to my music on Spotify and on iTunes,
Dialogue: 0,0:14:22.56,0:14:26.21,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}and also a playlist right here on YouTube as well.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:26.21,0:14:28.71,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}Add it to a playlist of summer and let me know what you think.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:28.71,0:14:30.42,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}Thanks everybody, that's gonna do it for me.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:30.42,0:14:32.60,1080P-src-hans-sans-Bold-50,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}I'm Tim Dodd, the everyday astronaut,
Comment: 0,0:00:00.11,0:00:02.18,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}英文字幕
Dialogue: 0,0:00:00.11,0:00:02.18,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4} - 嗨 我是Tim Dodd 每日宇航员
Dialogue: 0,0:00:02.18,0:00:07.21,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}距离尼尔阿姆斯特朗从阿波罗月球着陆器的脚垫上著名地走下已经有50年了
Dialogue: 0,0:00:07.21,0:00:11.87,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}在人类历史上首次探访别的天体
Dialogue: 0,0:00:11.87,0:00:14.08,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}而当他刚安全地站到月球表面上时
Dialogue: 0,0:00:14.08,0:00:17.67,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}他说了一些也许有史以来最有名的话
Dialogue: 0,0:00:17.67,0:00:25.76,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4} -  [尼尔阿姆斯特朗]这是我个人的一个小步 (但却是)人类的一大步
Dialogue: 0,0:00:25.76,0:00:28.29,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4} - 可这件事总是困扰着我
Dialogue: 0,0:00:28.29,0:00:34.55,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}没错 走下登月舱的91厘米脚垫是一个很方便的一小步
Dialogue: 0,0:00:34.55,0:00:38.38,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}但在那之前的一步则很巨大
Dialogue: 0,0:00:38.38,0:00:39.86,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}我说的是这个
Dialogue: 0,0:00:39.86,0:00:43.50,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}最后一个梯级与地面之间的巨大差距
Dialogue: 0,0:00:43.50,0:00:47.29,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}为什么在月球上会有这么大的差距？
Dialogue: 0,0:00:47.29,0:00:50.82,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}要求宇航员跳下到表面是不是很危险
Dialogue: 0,0:00:50.82,0:00:52.51,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}甚至还要再向上跳回来
Dialogue: 0,0:00:52.51,0:00:54.47,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}登月舱的梯子有九个梯级
Dialogue: 0,0:00:54.47,0:00:58.18,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}它们的间隔都是22.8厘米
Dialogue: 0,0:00:58.18,0:01:01.00,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}但最后一个梯级与地面之间的空隙
Dialogue: 0,0:01:01.00,0:01:05.36,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}大约是之前的三倍 高达76厘米
Dialogue: 0,0:01:05.36,0:01:09.07,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}实话说 这梯子不只是缺了一级
Dialogue: 0,0:01:09.07,0:01:10.41,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}是缺了两级
Dialogue: 0,0:01:10.41,0:01:12.97,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}没错 月球重力只有地球的六分之一
Dialogue: 0,0:01:12.97,0:01:17.38,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}但哪怕只是多一级梯子都安全很多
Dialogue: 0,0:01:17.38,0:01:19.60,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}只要少一点空隙都好
Dialogue: 0,0:01:19.60,0:01:20.97,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}那么我们今天来看看
Dialogue: 0,0:01:20.97,0:01:25.15,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}为什么NA​​SA和登月器的制造商格鲁曼公司选择这个长度的梯子
Dialogue: 0,0:01:25.15,0:01:28.43,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}然后 我们将讨论硬件的所有设计考虑
Dialogue: 0,0:01:28.43,0:01:31.45,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}月面本身的未知的条件
Dialogue: 0,0:01:31.45,0:01:35.57,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}还是说作为驾驶员的宇航员们都太熟练了
Dialogue: 0,0:01:35.57,0:01:39.42,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}不需要多余的那一级梯子来靠近月表
Dialogue: 0,0:01:39.42,0:01:40.35,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}让我们开始吧
Dialogue: 0,0:01:51.83,0:01:53.79,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4} - 在1961年5月25日
Dialogue: 0,0:01:53.79,0:01:56.06,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}约翰肯尼迪总统宣布了他的目标
Dialogue: 0,0:01:56.06,0:01:59.52,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}跟国会说 在十年内把人类送到月球
Dialogue: 0,0:01:59.52,0:02:02.34,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}在这个历史性的雄心勃勃的通告发生之时
Dialogue: 0,0:02:02.34,0:02:08.07,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}美国恰好只有15分22秒的载人航天经验
Dialogue: 0,0:02:08.07,0:02:11.36,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}而且只是一次亚轨道的经验
Dialogue: 0,0:02:11.36,0:02:14.40,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}顺便说一句 肯尼迪在国会前的讲话
Dialogue: 0,0:02:14.40,0:02:17.44,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}不是那个著名的 {\i1}我们选择登月{\i0} 的讲话
Dialogue: 0,0:02:17.44,0:02:20.77,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}这事发生在国会讲话的一年之后 在休斯敦的赖斯体育场
Dialogue: 0,0:02:20.77,0:02:25.44,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}但问题是这种疯狂雄心勃勃的目标导致很多东西很快开始(同时)做
Dialogue: 0,0:02:25.44,0:02:27.81,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}工程的海啸接踵而至
Dialogue: 0,0:02:27.81,0:02:28.94,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}(展开)太多工作的话
Dialogue: 0,0:02:28.94,0:02:32.33,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}感觉就像左手不知右手
Dialogue: 0,0:02:32.33,0:02:36.70,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}其中一个立刻开始研发的项目是月球着陆器
Dialogue: 0,0:02:36.70,0:02:41.75,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}1962年7月 11家公司被要求提交月球着陆器的计划
Dialogue: 0,0:02:41.75,0:02:46.42,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}格鲁曼公司赢得了合同 并早在1963年开始设计实体模型
Dialogue: 0,0:02:46.42,0:02:49.65,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}等等 这些和梯子有啥关系
Dialogue: 0,0:02:49.65,0:02:51.51,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}稳住 我要把这里的(背景)故事说完
Dialogue: 0,0:02:51.51,0:02:55.16,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}有一半的成份是这些故事蕴含着历史的乐趣
Dialogue: 0,0:02:55.16,0:03:00.57,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}但是这段历史是解释梯子长度问题的关键所在
Dialogue: 0,0:03:00.57,0:03:06.46,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}格鲁曼公司正在建造的着陆器需要着陆在一种我们一无所知的表面上
Dialogue: 0,0:03:06.46,0:03:09.17,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}这是可以理解的 我们当时唯一的数据
Dialogue: 0,0:03:09.17,0:03:11.98,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}是从绕月轨道器 徘徊者系列任务那里得到的
Dialogue: 0,0:03:11.98,0:03:15.87,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}而在这之前 只是靠地面的望远镜
Dialogue: 0,0:03:15.87,0:03:21.46,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}好吧 其实徘徊者6号到9号撞月前拍下的连续镜头
Dialogue: 0,0:03:21.46,0:03:26.05,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}带来了许多分辨率高达0.3米的影像
Dialogue: 0,0:03:26.05,0:03:31.10,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}但是我们仍未知道那时的月亮的表面如何
Dialogue: 0,0:03:31.10,0:03:33.42,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}直到1966年6月2日
Dialogue: 0,0:03:33.42,0:03:36.31,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}美国的勘测者号在月球软着陆
Dialogue: 0,0:03:36.31,0:03:39.32,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}差不多是苏联的月球9号着陆4个月后
Dialogue: 0,0:03:39.32,0:03:45.04,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}这也是美国第一次有了能了解月球表面构成的数据
Dialogue: 0,0:03:45.04,0:03:47.78,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}即使如此 这也是非常有限的
Dialogue: 0,0:03:47.78,0:03:50.54,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}这意味着在最初三年的月球着陆器的开发
Dialogue: 0,0:03:50.54,0:03:53.12,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}有无数的问题
Dialogue: 0,0:03:53.12,0:03:56.37,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}许多科学家认为表面可能是如此柔软 粉状的
Dialogue: 0,0:03:56.37,0:04:01.35,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}它可能让人或者航天器完全陷入
Dialogue: 0,0:04:01.35,0:04:03.82,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}以至于无法逃脱
Dialogue: 0,0:04:03.82,0:04:07.36,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}虽然NASA正忙着把飞船发去观测月球
Dialogue: 0,0:04:07.36,0:04:10.14,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}格鲁门公司则在深入地开发月球着陆器
Dialogue: 0,0:04:10.14,0:04:12.46,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}开发的前几年 方案就发生了很大变化
Dialogue: 0,0:04:12.46,0:04:16.00,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}像是把五条腿改成四条腿
Dialogue: 0,0:04:16.00,0:04:19.49,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}球形的座舱改成多面体的
Dialogue: 0,0:04:19.49,0:04:22.63,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}甚至还有把圆形舱门改成方形的
Dialogue: 0,0:04:22.63,0:04:27.62,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}顺便说下 圆形舱门让宇航员很难返回航天器
Dialogue: 0,0:04:27.62,0:04:32.94,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}所以格鲁曼改成了方门的方案 方便出入
Dialogue: 0,0:04:32.94,0:04:38.01,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}与此同时 格鲁曼公司也在使用绳子而非梯子
Dialogue: 0,0:04:38.01,0:04:41.32,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}而宇航员发现使用绳子是极度困难的
Dialogue: 0,0:04:41.32,0:04:45.90,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}尽管他们已经使用了 {\i1}彼得潘{\i0} 那样的滑轮系统 来模拟六分之一重力
Dialogue: 0,0:04:45.90,0:04:49.62,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}于是格鲁曼公司选择了在着陆器的前腿下安装梯子
Dialogue: 0,0:04:49.62,0:04:52.09,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}即使是梯子这般简单的东西
Dialogue: 0,0:04:52.09,0:04:54.16,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}重量也是大问题
Dialogue: 0,0:04:54.16,0:04:57.58,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}毕竟(发射)着陆到月球上的1kg质量
Dialogue: 0,0:04:57.58,0:05:01.40,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}就需要大概400kg的火箭质量
Dialogue: 0,0:05:01.40,0:05:03.91,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}这意味着格鲁曼公司费了九牛二虎之力 以减轻重量
Dialogue: 0,0:05:03.95,0:05:08.80,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}包括不用座椅和使用轻的金色聚酰亚胺薄膜作绝缘材料
Dialogue: 0,0:05:08.80,0:05:12.10,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}于是梯子也一样
Dialogue: 0,0:05:12.10,0:05:14.41,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}也需要极端减重
Dialogue: 0,0:05:14.41,0:05:16.33,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}例如 我最喜欢去思考的是
Dialogue: 0,0:05:16.40,0:05:19.44,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}如果登月舱在地球上用着陆腿支撑
Dialogue: 0,0:05:19.44,0:05:21.53,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}会因为他们自身的质量而倒塌
Dialogue: 0,0:05:21.53,0:05:24.53,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}因为那些腿并不是按照地球引力的标准设计的
Dialogue: 0,0:05:24.53,0:05:27.36,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}而是按照较弱的月球引力设计的
Dialogue: 0,0:05:27.36,0:05:29.04,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}对于梯子也是一样
Dialogue: 0,0:05:29.04,0:05:32.43,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}如果我们在地球上试图登上那个梯子
Dialogue: 0,0:05:32.43,0:05:36.05,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}很可能它会因为地球引力更大的情况而坏掉
Dialogue: 0,0:05:36.05,0:05:37.75,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}因此 他们把梯子做得尽量地轻
Dialogue: 0,0:05:37.75,0:05:40.91,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}这样就只能应付六分之一的重力
Dialogue: 0,0:05:40.91,0:05:45.04,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}但是重量并非最后一级距离表面较远的主要原因
Dialogue: 0,0:05:45.04,0:05:48.34,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}对于这一点 我们需要看看贴着梯子的那个起落架
Dialogue: 0,0:05:48.34,0:05:50.76,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}起落架被设计用来吸收碰撞能量
Dialogue: 0,0:05:50.76,0:05:52.94,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}并防止登月舱翻倒
Dialogue: 0,0:05:52.94,0:05:56.64,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}格鲁门公司的工程师们非常关心登月舱的翻倒问题
Dialogue: 0,0:05:56.64,0:06:00.08,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}因此起落架的设计花费了不少工作
Dialogue: 0,0:06:00.08,0:06:04.75,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}起落架是如此重要 在登月舱和指令舱分离时
Dialogue: 0,0:06:04.75,0:06:09.23,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}指令舱的驾驶员会被命令进行着陆腿的目视检查
Dialogue: 0,0:06:09.23,0:06:12.30,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}以确保他们正确地从(之前的)折叠状态展开
Dialogue: 0,0:06:12.30,0:06:16.06,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}如果着陆腿没有锁到正确的位置 任务就会马上终止
Dialogue: 0,0:06:16.06,0:06:18.62,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}不过幸运的是 没有一次发生过这样的情况
Dialogue: 0,0:06:18.62,0:06:23.16,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}一个有趣的设计考虑是一次性减震器的发明
Dialogue: 0,0:06:23.16,0:06:26.90,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}NASA和格鲁曼公司研制了一种可压碎的蜂窝状铝筒
Dialogue: 0,0:06:26.90,0:06:28.50,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}也被称为粉碎芯
Dialogue: 0,0:06:28.50,0:06:31.37,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}如果在起落架上使用液压装置
Dialogue: 0,0:06:31.37,0:06:34.55,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}一旦液体泄漏 可能会导致着陆腿无法使用
Dialogue: 0,0:06:34.55,0:06:39.83,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}因此 为了简单起见 他们使用了粉碎芯 基本上是一组填充物
Dialogue: 0,0:06:39.83,0:06:44.88,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}由铝做成的 以提供平滑和可靠的拉力或压力
Dialogue: 0,0:06:44.88,0:06:48.02,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}这种技术至今仍在特定领域使用
Dialogue: 0,0:06:48.02,0:06:53.03,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}实际上 SpaceX的猎鹰9号着陆腿里就有这样的结构
Dialogue: 0,0:06:53.03,0:06:55.36,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}如果液压减震器失灵了
Dialogue: 0,0:06:55.36,0:06:58.43,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}还能使用粉碎芯的额外行程(来减震)
Dialogue: 0,0:06:58.43,0:07:00.60,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}在Thaicom 8任务中很明显
Dialogue: 0,0:07:00.60,0:07:04.23,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}这是发生在2016年5月27日的任务 同日发射同日降落
Dialogue: 0,0:07:04.23,0:07:06.96,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}一级火箭的降落有点粗暴
Dialogue: 0,0:07:06.96,0:07:10.40,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}导致其中一个着陆腿使用了粉碎核心
Dialogue: 0,0:07:10.40,0:07:12.82,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}使得一级火箭站得有点倾斜
Dialogue: 0,0:07:12.82,0:07:16.14,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}某种奇迹之下 一级火箭一路拖回了家
Dialogue: 0,0:07:16.14,0:07:19.46,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}尽管有好几次差点掉水了
Dialogue: 0,0:07:26.41,0:07:27.75,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}话题回到登月舱
Dialogue: 0,0:07:27.75,0:07:31.09,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}它的着陆腿能吸收大量的冲击速度
Dialogue: 0,0:07:31.09,0:07:33.03,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}得益于其粉碎核心这种(特殊)减震器
Dialogue: 0,0:07:33.03,0:07:36.13,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}它们不会像传统的液压减震器那样反弹
Dialogue: 0,0:07:36.13,0:07:39.09,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}它们压缩之后就会在原地停下
Dialogue: 0,0:07:39.09,0:07:44.37,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}设计上 它们能承受3m/s的垂直速度和0m/s的水平速度
Dialogue: 0,0:07:44.37,0:07:50.62,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}或者是2.1m/s的垂直速度和1.2m/s的水平速度
Dialogue: 0,0:07:50.62,0:07:52.63,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}在这个限度以内 可靠性很好
Dialogue: 0,0:07:52.63,0:07:57.02,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}因为NASA并不知道减震器行程会有多少
Dialogue: 0,0:07:57.02,0:08:01.13,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}而且他们也不知道月表会塌陷多少
Dialogue: 0,0:08:01.13,0:08:04.71,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}他们不想让梯子贴在着陆腿的可移动部分上面
Dialogue: 0,0:08:04.71,0:08:06.75,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}这会阻碍着陆腿的活动
Dialogue: 0,0:08:06.75,0:08:11.39,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}事实上 NASA给着陆腿留了很大的伸缩量
Dialogue: 0,0:08:11.39,0:08:15.47,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}最后发现 两个因素减少了着陆腿的伸缩量
Dialogue: 0,0:08:15.47,0:08:20.51,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}驾驶员的技能和月表吸收能量的能力
Dialogue: 0,0:08:20.51,0:08:21.40,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}没错
Dialogue: 0,0:08:21.40,0:08:27.26,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}驾驶员对待登月舱非常温柔 他们着陆得如此轻柔
Dialogue: 0,0:08:27.26,0:08:30.49,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}着陆腿几乎没有发生伸缩
Dialogue: 0,0:08:30.49,0:08:33.38,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}不过话说回来 面对未知
Dialogue: 0,0:08:33.38,0:08:36.49,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}NASA希望(着陆)这件事非常安全
Dialogue: 0,0:08:36.49,0:08:38.49,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}宇航员们被要求关闭引擎
Dialogue: 0,0:08:38.51,0:08:44.64,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}当3个1.5米长的月表探头和月表发生接触时
Dialogue: 0,0:08:44.64,0:08:47.34,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}你可能听他们说过这样的 {\i1}接触{\i0} 呼号
Dialogue: 0,0:09:01.84,0:09:03.20,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}这样做 不仅是为了
Dialogue: 0,0:09:03.22,0:09:08.97,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}防止发动机吹起太多的碎屑和灰尘 影响能见度或者破坏地表
Dialogue: 0,0:09:08.97,0:09:12.43,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}也是因为发动机有推力衰减
Dialogue: 0,0:09:12.43,0:09:15.31,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}即使在发动机停机成功后
Dialogue: 0,0:09:15.31,0:09:20.42,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}其仍有半秒到数秒的时间保持一定的推力
Dialogue: 0,0:09:20.42,0:09:21.96,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}所有火箭发动机都有这个问题
Dialogue: 0,0:09:21.96,0:09:22.79,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}有趣地是
Dialogue: 0,0:09:22.79,0:09:26.03,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}在试车台上 额外的推力衰减往往被忽略
Dialogue: 0,0:09:26.03,0:09:30.95,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}当SpaceX在猎鹰1号火箭的第二次和第三次之间升级了他们的梅林发动机
Dialogue: 0,0:09:30.95,0:09:32.01,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}安全分离后
Dialogue: 0,0:09:32.01,0:09:35.92,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}额外的推力衰减导致了第一级和第二级之间的碰撞
Dialogue: 0,0:09:35.92,0:09:37.55,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}导致发射失败
Dialogue: 0,0:09:37.55,0:09:41.73,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}阿波罗计划的指令长们被要求在1.5米高度关闭发动机
Dialogue: 0,0:09:41.73,0:09:45.14,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}可以让它以正确的高度 安全的速度触地
Dialogue: 0,0:09:45.14,0:09:49.35,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}与此同时让着陆腿压缩在一个NASA认为是安全的范围之内
Dialogue: 0,0:09:49.35,0:09:50.65,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}但是 除此之外
Dialogue: 0,0:09:50.65,0:09:54.32,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}6次着陆都有着不同的冲击速度
Dialogue: 0,0:09:54.32,0:09:56.79,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}尼尔阿姆斯特朗参与的阿波罗11号任务着陆最柔软
Dialogue: 0,0:09:56.79,0:10:00.15,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}垂直速度仅0.54m/s
Dialogue: 0,0:10:00.15,0:10:04.69,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}其次是阿波罗17号的0.91m/s
Dialogue: 0,0:10:04.69,0:10:08.51,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}然后是阿波罗14号的0.94m/s
Dialogue: 0,0:10:08.51,0:10:11.42,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}阿波罗12号的1m/s
Dialogue: 0,0:10:11.42,0:10:14.30,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}阿波罗16号的1.7m/s
Dialogue: 0,0:10:14.30,0:10:22.47,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}最后 阿波罗15号的指令长戴维斯科特达到了2.07m/s
Dialogue: 0,0:10:22.47,0:10:25.51,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}但这仍在操作范围之中
Dialogue: 0,0:10:25.51,0:10:30.01,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}还有个问题是下降级发动机会和月表发生接触
Dialogue: 0,0:10:30.01,0:10:34.62,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}尽管阿波罗15号有着携带月球车的附加质量
Dialogue: 0,0:10:34.62,0:10:38.26,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}下降级发动机有着(相比之前任务)长了的25厘米的喷嘴
Dialogue: 0,0:10:38.26,0:10:41.48,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}进行了达到11度倾斜 也是最陡峭的降落
Dialogue: 0,0:10:41.48,0:10:44.72,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}尽管喷嘴实际上有点弯曲变形
Dialogue: 0,0:10:44.72,0:10:48.76,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}喷嘴仍未与表面有任何接触
Dialogue: 0,0:10:48.76,0:10:51.30,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}喷嘴的弯曲变形是因为
Dialogue: 0,0:10:51.30,0:10:53.89,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}过于接近地面的点火造成的压力的聚集
Dialogue: 0,0:10:53.89,0:10:56.87,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}而不是和表面发生的接触
Dialogue: 0,0:10:56.87,0:11:00.92,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}(除了驾驶员的技巧)关于(着陆)压力没有这么大的另一个原因则是
Dialogue: 0,0:11:00.92,0:11:04.09,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}较为粉末状的月表
Dialogue: 0,0:11:04.09,0:11:09.69,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}吸收了差不多80%的冲击速度
Dialogue: 0,0:11:09.69,0:11:13.89,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}这也是为什么着陆腿的压缩远小于之前预计的
Dialogue: 0,0:11:13.89,0:11:16.22,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}(而这所有的一切)导致最后一级梯子比正常情况下的要高
Dialogue: 0,0:11:16.22,0:11:18.53,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}这个故事想表达的是
Dialogue: 0,0:11:18.53,0:11:22.32,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}阿波罗计划中的登月那部分问题重重
Dialogue: 0,0:11:22.32,0:11:26.37,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}NASA采取了最保守的方法 以尽可能多的冗余
Dialogue: 0,0:11:26.37,0:11:28.46,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}包括未能证明自己的减震器
Dialogue: 0,0:11:28.46,0:11:30.77,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}着陆腿上额外的热保护层
Dialogue: 0,0:11:30.77,0:11:32.03,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}较大的着陆脚垫
Dialogue: 0,0:11:32.03,0:11:34.11,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}还有接触探头等等
Dialogue: 0,0:11:34.11,0:11:37.52,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}只是说 他们确实是不想要梯子
Dialogue: 0,0:11:37.52,0:11:40.24,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}超出必要的长度导致对着陆腿运动潜在的影响
Dialogue: 0,0:11:40.24,0:11:44.05,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}假设计划和现实一致 减震器也没有这么夸张
Dialogue: 0,0:11:44.05,0:11:47.06,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}梯子(的最后一级)跨过去(也会比现在)容易很多
Dialogue: 0,0:11:47.06,0:11:51.23,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}尽管如此 最后一步还是对一些宇航员造成了不少困扰
Dialogue: 0,0:11:51.23,0:11:56.19,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}指令长在训练中被要求尝试立刻跳回最后一级梯子
Dialogue: 0,0:11:56.19,0:11:58.52,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}在第一次触地之后
Dialogue: 0,0:11:58.52,0:12:04.08,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}这样的话 如果跳下这么大的空隙造成了任何问题 还在登月舱里的驾驶员就能帮助他
Dialogue: 0,0:12:04.08,0:12:07.96,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}尼尔在他走下登月舱的脚垫之前还对此作出了评论
Dialogue: 0,0:12:25.68,0:12:28.25,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}不同的宇航员有着不同的爬梯体验
Dialogue: 0,0:12:28.25,0:12:31.29,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}如吉姆欧文说 梯子真是个麻烦事
Dialogue: 0,0:12:31.29,0:12:34.18,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}而身高170cm的皮特康拉德说
Dialogue: 0,0:12:39.50,0:12:43.05,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}总结下 最后一级梯子的高度是个争议性话题
Dialogue: 0,0:12:43.05,0:12:44.69,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}但是面对未知
Dialogue: 0,0:12:44.69,0:12:48.52,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}也是为了节省载具的质量
Dialogue: 0,0:12:48.52,0:12:54.33,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}而六分之一重力下的跳跃又会使得这一切变得容易
Dialogue: 0,0:12:54.33,0:12:58.15,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}还有就是他们不知道月表会吸收多少能量
Dialogue: 0,0:12:58.15,0:13:03.00,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}所以最后NASA把最后一级梯子留了76cm的高度
Dialogue: 0,0:13:03.00,0:13:06.06,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}也就是梯子的底部到着陆脚垫的距离
Dialogue: 0,0:13:06.06,0:13:07.48,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}或者NASA只需要
Dialogue: 0,0:13:07.48,0:13:12.91,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}像苏联计划对他们的LK月球着陆器做的那样 使用一个铰链式的(伸缩)梯子
Dialogue: 0,0:13:12.91,0:13:13.89,1080P-src-hans-sans-medi-75,,0,0,0,,{\blur4}所以你怎么看？
